{
  "Aggressive Escort": {
    "rank": 1,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": null,
    "skill": null,
    "flavor": """
      The first duty of a protective detail is positioning: stand between the threat and the principal, collapse the sightlines, make yourself the problem. But if someone shoots at you anyway, it would be foolish not to answer.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you perform a Guard action while within range 0–1 of the character you are guarding, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>(op):</strong> After a character performs an Attack action targeting you or the character you are guarding, you may perform a Strike action with one readied weapon targeting that character. This effect persists until the start of your next turn, or until you perform a Strike action this way.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Defensive Maneuver": {
    "rank": 1,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Resilience",
    "skill": null,
    "flavor": """
      Sometimes all else fails and you take a nasty hit. Twisting your body, raising an arm, anything to deflect the blow just enough to avoid the worst of it separates a survivor from a casualty.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make a check to resist a critical strike, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>(op):</strong> If you reduce the critical strike’s severity to 0, you do not suffer the effects of the critical strike.</li>
        <li><strong>(op):</strong> If you would suffer the Bleeding condition as a result of the critical strike, you do not suffer that condition, and instead suffer the Dazed condition.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Let It Ride": {
    "rank": 1,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Fortune",
    "skill": "Resolve",
    "flavor": """
      Everything in combat is a game of chance, failing to recognize that fact creates undue stress on an operator. Learning to let go and accept the whims of fate can be a powerful tool for maintaining composure and seizing opportunities that others might miss.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      Once per scene, after you perform an action that does not require a check, while in a Fortune Posture, you may make a <strong> TN 1 Resolve (Fortune)</strong> check.</p>
      <h3>Effects:</h3>
      <p>If you succeed, the next time you would gain strife, reduce the amount you recieve by 3, plus 1 per two bonus successes. This effect persists until the start of your next turn.</p>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fortune (op):</strong> This effect applies each time you would receive strife before the start of your next turn instead.</li>
        <li><strong>Fortune (op)(op):</strong> You may use this technique one additional time this scene.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Pistol Whip": {
    "rank": 1,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Power",
    "skill": "Conditioning",
    "flavor": """
      A gun is not just a tool for shooting. It can also be a blunt instrument, a symbol of authority, and a source of intimidation. A well-placed pistol whip can disarm an opponent, break their concentration, or simply remind them who's in charge.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>As an Attack and Support action using a readied firearm, you may make a <strong>TN 3 Conditioning (Resilience) check</strong> targeting one character at range 0.</p>
      <h3>Effects:</h3>
      <p>If you succeed, your target suffers physical damage equal to 5 plus your bonus successes with deadliness 2.</p>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Power (op)(op)+:</strong> Your target must resist with a <strong>TN 4 Conditioning check (Precision 2, Swiftness 5)</strong> or be pushed 1 range band away from you per (op)(op) spent this way.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Shoot to Maim": {
    "rank": 1,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Precision",
    "skill": null,
    "flavor": """
      Not every shot is meant to kill. A well-placed round to the knee, shoulder, or hand achieves something a lethal shot cannot: it leaves the opponent present, suffering, and in the way.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>While you perform an Attack action check, you may spend (op) as follows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Precision (op)(op):</strong> Choose one of the following conditions: Bleeding, Dazed, Disoriented, Prone. If this check inflicts that condition on one or more targets, those targets cannot remove that condition until the end of your next turn.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Sighting-in": {
    "rank": 1,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Swiftness",
    "skill": "Firearms",
    "flavor": """
      Combat doctrine favors placing pieces on the board where they'll be most effective, but rarely does reality play out like a game. A marksman who can adapt to less-than-ideal conditions and still put rounds on target is a valuable asset to any team.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When making a ranged attack using the Swiftness approach, you may spend opportunity in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Swiftness (op)(op):</strong> Reduce the TN penalty for attacking targets outside your weapon's ideal range by 1. This effect lasts until you move or until the end of the scene, whichever comes first.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Splat!": {
    "rank": 1,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Resilience",
    "skill": "Exotic Weapons",
    "flavor": """
      It's not practical on a modern battlefield, but you can't deny that a giant fucking hammer is a great way to make an impression.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make an Attack action using a melee-type Exotic weapon, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Resilience (op):</strong> If you fail, your target suffers physical damage equal to your ranks in Conditioning.</li>
        <li><strong>Resilience (op):</strong> If you succeed and your target is Prone, increase the damage you deal by your ranks in Fitness. </li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Throwing Knife": {
    "rank": 1,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": null,
    "skill": "Blades",
    "flavor": """
      A throwing knife is a versatile weapon that can be used for both offense and defense. A well-aimed throw can take out an opponent from a distance, while a quick toss can create an opening in an opponent's defense or distract them long enough to make a follow-up attack.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>As an Attack action using one readied Knife in a one-handed grip, you may make a <strong>TN 2 Blades</strong> check targeting one character at range 1.</p>
      <h3>Effects:</h3>
      <p>You hurl your knife at the target.</p>
      <p>If you succeed, you deal physical damage to the target equal to the Knife’s base damage plus your bonus successes. The Knife lands at range in a direction of your choice from the target if they defend against the damage, or embeds in them if they suffer a critical strike.</p>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Precision (op)+:</strong> Reduce the TN of the next attack action against the target before the end of your next turn by 1.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Whirling Strike": {
    "rank": 1,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Swiftness",
    "skill": "Melee Combat",
    "flavor": """
      A spinning attack can be a powerful way to strike multiple opponents at once, or to create an opening in an opponent's defense. The momentum of the spin can add extra force to your strike, making it more difficult to block or dodge.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make an Attack action using an Exotic weapon, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Swiftness (op)+:</strong> If you succeed and your target is a minion, your target suffers additional damage equal to the deadliness of your weapon.</li>
        <li><strong>Swiftness (op)+:</strong> If you fail and your target's ranks in Resolve are less than or equal to (op) spent this way, your target receives strife equal to the deadliness of your weapon.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Acrobatic Recovery": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": [
      "Swiftness",
      "Resilience"
    ],
    "skill": null,
    "flavor": """
      A skilled fighter can turn a bad situation into an opportunity. Whether it's rolling with a fall, twisting out of a grapple, or using the momentum of a hit to spring back to their feet, they can recover from conditions that would leave others vulnerable.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make a Combat skill check using the Swiftness or Resilience approach, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Swiftness or Resilience (op)+:</strong> Remove one Disoriented or Prone condition from yourself per (op) spent this way.</li>
        <li><strong>Swiftness or Resilience (op):</strong> If the check would cause you to suffer the Disoriented or Prone condition, you do not suffer it.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Airborne Assault": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Swiftness",
    "skill": "Firearms",
    "flavor": """
      You would be suprised just how often a target doesn't look up. Flight remains an unexpected movement in many encounters, and those who can harness it, via jetpack, grappling hook, or just a well-timed leap, can strike from angles their opponent isn't prepared for.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      While you perform a Strike action while 1 or more range bands above your target, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Swiftness (op)+:</strong> Choose 1 of your targets per (op) spent this way. That target suffers the Disoriented condition.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Battle in the Mind": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Fortune",
    "skill": null,
    "flavor": """
      An elite who has survived enough engagements learns to recognize the signals an opponent does not intend to reveal: the posture, the hesitation, the split-second flicker of the eyes. By the time the first shot is fired, a plan is already in motion.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make an Initiative check for a duel using your Fortune Approach, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fortune (op):</strong> Name two approaches. Your opponent must choose one, and cannot select it as their posture during their first turn of the duel.</li>
        <li><strong>Fortune (op)+:</strong> Choose a technique category. Learn one of your opponent's known techniques of that category (chosen by the opponent) per (op) spent this way.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Closing Strike": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": null,
    "skill": "Blades",
    "flavor": """
      Many would mistake distance from a blade user for safety, but a true master of the sword can cover ground in the blink of an eye, crossing surprising gaps.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>As a Movement and Attack action while wielding a readied bladed weapon, you may make a <strong>TN 3 Blades (Swiftness)</strong> check targeting one character at range 1–3.</p>
      <h3>Effects:</h3>
      <p>If you succeed, you move into melee range with your target (range 0) and your target suffers physical damage equal to your Swiftness approach value. The target must resist with a <strong>TN 4 Conditioning check (TN 2 Resilience, TN 5 Power)</strong>; if they fail, increase the physical damage they suffer by your weapon's base damage.</p>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Swiftness (op):</strong> Remove the Dazed, Disoriented, Immobilized, or Prone condition from yourself.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Crushing Blow": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Power",
    "skill": "Exotic Weapons",
    "flavor": """
      A powerful strike with a heavy weapon can do more than just deal damage. It can break through defenses, shatter armor, and leave the target vulnerable to follow-up attacks.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make an Attack action using a melee-type Exotic weapon, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Power (op)(op):</strong> If you succeed, choose one defensive item your target is using (such as armor they are wearing or a readied shield they are wielding). The item receives the Damaged item quality; if it is already Damaged, it becomes Destroyed instead. </li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Disarming Shot": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Precision",
    "skill": "Firearms",
    "flavor": """
      Shooting a weapon out of someone's hand is, by any reasonable assessment, an extremely difficult shot. The angle, the timing, the margin for error, most marksmen will never attempt it. The ones who do either miss entirely or make it look easy.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>As an Attack action using a readied ranged weapon, you may make a <strong>TN 4 Firearms (Precision)</strong> check targeting one character within the weapon's range.</p>
      <h3>Effects:</h3>
      <p>If you succeed, your target suffers physical damage equal to your Precision, plus additional damage equal to your bonus successes. Choose one of your target's readied weapons; the target must resist with a <strong>TN 4 Conditioning check (Swiftness 2, Precision 5)</strong> or lose control of the chosen weapon, which travels 2 range bands in a direction of your choice.</p>
    """
  },
  "Distraction Tactics": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Resilience",
    "skill": "Tactics",
    "flavor": """
      To draw enemy fire onto yourself is a sacrifice few are willing to make. Those that do, however, open up a world of possibilities for their allies. A well-timed distraction can turn the tide of battle, allowing teammates to reposition, regroup, or strike with impunity while the enemy is focused on you.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>Once per Scene, as a support action using one readied weapon, you may make a <strong>Tactics (Resilience)</strong> check.</p>
      <h3>Effects:</h3>
      <p>If you succeed, other characters in the scene cannot select your allies as a target if they could select you instead. This effect persists for a number of rounds equal to your Fortification Value (minimum 1).</p>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Resilience (op)+:</strong> If you succeed, increase the TN of Attack and Scheme actions targeting you by 1 per (op) spent this way.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Eyes on the Prize": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Precision",
    "skill": "Insight",
    "flavor": """
      Knowing your enemy's weaknesses is one thing. Knowing their strengths is another. A skilled operator can identify the techniques their opponent relies on most, and use that information to exploit openings and create new opportunities in combat.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make a check to perform a Strike action, you may spend (op) as follows:</p>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Precision (op)+:</strong> If your target's vigilance is lower than your ranks in Insight plus the number of (op) spent this way, choose one of the following disclosure categories: <strong>approaches</strong> (learn one of the target's approach values), <strong>conditions</strong> (learn all conditions the target is currently suffering), or <strong>techniques</strong> (the target reveals one combat technique they possess, chosen by the target).</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Gap in the Armor": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": null,
    "skill": "Blades",
    "flavor": """
      Even the toughest armor has a weak point. A skilled fighter who can find and exploit that weak point can turn a heavily armored opponent into a sitting duck.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make an Attack Action using a Bladed weapon, you may spend (op) as follows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>(op)+:</strong> Your weapon ignores an amount of your target's armor equal to (op) spent this way.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Grappler": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Fortune",
    "skill": "Hand-to-Hand",
    "flavor": """
      Fighters who are unafraid to get down and dirty with their opponent can control the battlefield in ways that more cautious combatants cannot. A well-timed grapple can neutralize a threat, create an opening for an ally, or even turn an enemy into a makeshift shield.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>As an Attack action using unarmed or a readied melee weapon, you may make a <strong>Hand-to-Hand (Fortune)</strong> check targeting one character at range 0. The TN is equal to the silhouette of the target (Minimum 1).</p>
      <h3>Effects:</h3>
      <p>If you succeed, both you and the target suffer the Immobilized condition and you count as granting assistance to all characters who perform Attack actions against your target. This effect persists until the beginning of your next turn.</p>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fortune (op):</strong> If you succeed, your target must resist with a Conditioning check or suffer physical damage equal to its silhouette, ignoring resistance, and suffer the prone condition. The TN of this check is equal to your Fortification Value.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Guns Akimbo": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": null,
    "skill": "Firearms",
    "flavor": """
      Anyone can spray bullets with a gun in each hand. Hitting something that way takes a different breed of shooter entirely. The trick is not volume of fire, but timing: one muzzle keeps the target occupied while the other lands the shot that matters.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make a Firearms Attack action check, if you have a second readied weapon you did not use for the attack, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>(op)+:</strong> You must spend (op) equal to your target's vigilance to activate this technique. One target of your action suffers physical damage equal to the second readied weapon's base damage. If that target is Dazed, increase this damage by your ranks in Firearms.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Improvise Weapon": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Swiftness",
    "skill": "Survival",
    "flavor": """
      A fighter who can turn anything they find into a weapon is never without options. A broken bottle, a length of pipe, a discarded chair: all can be tools for survival in the right hands.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>As a Movement and Attack action, you may make a <strong>TN 2 Survival (Swiftness)</strong> check.</p>
      <h3>Effects:</h3>
      <p>If you succeed, you find and ready an improvised weapon of your choice, the GM has final say on what is available. The weapon's base damage is equal to your ranks in Survival, and it has the same range and deadliness as a typical melee weapon.</p>
      <p>The weapon persists until the end of the scene, at which point it gains the <strong>Destroyed</strong> quality.</p>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Swiftness (op)(op):</strong> You may immediately perform a Strike action using the readied weapon.</li>
        <li><strong>Swiftness (op)(op)(op):</strong> If you succeed, choose one of the following item qualities:
        <strong>Cumbersome</strong>, <strong>Razor-Edged</strong>, or <strong>Snaring</strong>. The readied weapon gains that quality for the duration.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Judo Throw": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Power",
    "skill": "Hand-to-Hand",
    "flavor": """
      A skilled martial artist can use an opponent's momentum against them, redirecting their own force to throw them off balance and slam them into the ground.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make a Blades or Hand-to-Hand attack against a target at range 0, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Power (op):</strong> If you succeed, your target must resist with a <strong>TN 4 Conditioning check (TN 3 Swiftness, TN 5 Power)</strong>. If they fail, they suffer the <strong>Prone</strong> condition and fatigue equal to their shortfall.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Landmine": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Precision",
    "skill": "Explosives",
    "flavor": """
      A well-placed mine does not need anyone behind it. It waits. Concealed beneath rubble, wedged under a floor panel, buried in a stretch of churned earth, it remains patient until the moment someone steps where they shouldn't. The blast radius does not distinguish between careless and informed.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>As a Movement and Support action, you may make a <strong>TN 3 Explosives (Precision)</strong> check and expend one explosive device you are carrying to place a concealed mine at a target position at range 0–1.</p>
      <h3>Effects:</h3>
      <p>If you succeed, the mine is hidden at the target position until the end of the scene. Mines detonate indiscriminately and cannot distinguish ally from enemy. A character who is actively searching may detect the mine with a <strong>Survival or Insight check</strong> with a TN equal to your bonus successes (minimum 1).</p>
      <p>When any character or unit enters range 0 of the target position, the mine detonates. Some or all of the following occur based on the scene type:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>(Skirmish/Other Scene)</strong> Each character at range 0–2 of the detonation point suffers physical damage equal to your ranks in Explosives plus your bonus successes, suffers the Dazed condition, and receives 3 strife. Items at range 0–1 of the detonation point gain the Damaged quality.</li>
        <li><strong>(Mass Battle)</strong> The unit that triggered the mine suffers a morale setback; their commander must immediately make a <strong>TN 3 Command check</strong> or that unit cannot be ordered this round. Additionally, that unit suffers casualties equal to your ranks in Explosives plus your bonus successes for the purpose of determining its combat effectiveness this round.</li>
        <li><strong>(Mass Battle)</strong> If the mine was placed inside or at the threshold of a fortification or chokepoint, reduce the effective defense value of that position by 1 for the remainder of the battle round.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>(op)(op):</strong> Any item or structure damaged by this effect gains the Destroyed quality instead of Damaged.</li>
        <li><strong>(op)(op):</strong> The area at range 0–2 of the detonation point gains the Dangerous and Obscuring terrain qualities until the end of the round.</li>
        <li><strong>(op)+:</strong> Increase the TN to detect the mine by 1 per (op) spent this way.</li>
        <li><strong>Precision (op):</strong> You place one additional mine within range 0–1 of the original position using the same check.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Last Stand": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Power",
    "skill": null,
    "flavor": """
      A fighter who is wounded but still standing is not a weakened threat. They are a desperate one. Pain strips away restraint, and what remains is something faster, uglier, and harder to predict than anything training produces.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make a check to resist a critical strike during a skirmish, if you are Enraged and not Incapacitated, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Power (op)+:</strong> Choose one of your unarmed profiles or a readied improvised weapon. Each other character at range 0–1 with vigilance lower than or equal to (op) spent this way suffers physical damage equal to the base damage of your unarmed profile plus 1 for each (op) spent in excess of their vigilance.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Momentous Strike": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Swiftness",
    "skill": "Blades",
    "flavor": """
      Momentum is a powerful force in combat. A fighter who can harness it, using the distance they have covered to strike with greater force, can turn their own movement into a weapon.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make an Attack action check using a bladed weapon, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Swiftness (op):</strong> If you succeed, treat the deadliness of your weapon as increased by the number of range bands you have traveled this round.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Murderous Intent": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Power",
    "skill": null,
    "flavor": """
      Combat is, in the most pure essence, the act of killing before being killed. A fighter who embraces that fact, who does not flinch at the thought of taking a life, can tap into a well of primal ferocity that makes them a terrifying opponent.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>As an attack and Movement action using a readied weapon, you may make a <strong> TN 4 Combat (Power)</strong> check using the appropriate skill for that weapon.</p>
      <h3>Effects:</h3>
      <p>If you succeed, your target suffers a critical strike with severity equal to your weapon's deadliness plus your bonus successes. The TN of the Conditioning check to resist this critical strike is 3 (Precision 4, Swiftness 1) instead of the normal TN. If you fail, you suffer the Disoriented condition.</p>
      <h3>New Opportunities:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Power (op):</strong> Before resolving the effect, move up to 1 range band toward your target.</li>
      </ul>
    """
  },
  "Rolling With the Punches": {
    "rank": 2,
    "type": "Combat",
    "approach": "Fortune",
    "skill": "Conditioning",
    "flavor": """
      The best way to survive a hit is to not be there when it lands. The second best way is to be there, but not be a rigid target for it. A flexible defense can turn an opponent's strength against them, reducing the damage you take and maybe even creating an opening for a counterattack.
    """,
    "description": """
      <h3>Activation:</h3>
      <p>When you make a Conditioning check to resist a critical strike caused by another character's attack, you may spend (op) in the following way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fortune (op)+:</strong> You may reduce the critical strike by an additional point per (op)(op) spent this way</li>
      </ul>
